using this cyclic quadrilateral, this rhombus and F-angles, with directed angles if need be:

\[
\begin{align*}
\angle S'XY &= 180^\circ - \angle S'B'Y = 180^\circ - \angle S'B'B - \angle BB'Y \\
&= \angle BDC - \angle YBB' = \angle DBA + \angle BAD - \angle BDA \\
&= \angle BAC.
\end{align*}
\]

Analogously, it holds that $\angle S'YX = \angle BCA$. So $\triangle XYS' \sim \triangle ACB$, so the condition $|AB| + |BC| = 4|AC|$ also holds in $\triangle XYS'$. We conclude that $|XY'| = |XS'| + |S'Y| = 4|XY|$, which is exactly what we wanted to show. $\square$
